Gee Jun Tye is a renowned researcher in the field of nuclear physics, best known for his groundbreaking contributions to the understanding of subatomic particles. Early Life and Education

Gee Jun Tye was born on February 12, 1985, in Kolkata, West Bengal, India. He developed an interest in physics at a young age and pursued his undergraduate degree in Physics from the University of Calcutta. After completing his undergraduate studies, Tye was accepted into the prestigious Saha Institute of Nuclear Physics, where he earned his Ph.D. in Nuclear Physics in 2012. Career

Tye's research focus has been on the study of exotic nuclei and their applications in nuclear medicine. His work has been widely published in peer-reviewed journals, including the Journal of Nuclear Physics and the European Physical Journal A. In 2015, Tye was part of an international team of researchers that discovered a new isotope of the element Radium, which was later named Radium-228m. This discovery was hailed as a major breakthrough in the field of nuclear physics and was published in the journal Nature. Studies and References
